\section{Introduction}

Social security legislation was first introduced at the end of the 19th century in France, with a law, passed in 1898, protecting workers against work accidents, and granting them damages by recognizing the employers' responsibility. More comprehensive systems then developed: first old-age insurance for industry and agriculture workers was created in 1910, and a broader system of insurance against risks of sickness, maternity, disability and old-age was created for wage-earners of trade and industry in 1930.\\
Beside these general measures and even before the drafting of the first legislation, autonomous initiatives from workers or employers emerged for some types of occupations (public firms such as the electricity and gas firm, the public company for Parisian transportation, self-employed workers, farm workers, civil-servants, etc.) in the form of mutual insurance organizations. Proper pension systems were established in the 19$^{th}$ century, whose membership was related to the occupation of workers: for employees of the \textit{Banque de France} (French central bank) (1806), for actors at the \textit{Com\'edie fran\c{c}aise} (1812), for civil servants (1853), for railways' employees (1855), and for miners (1894). They were sometimes linked with the introduction of sickness insurance.\\
This variety of schemes has been maintained even after the development of a general system encompassing the majority of the population, and helps understanding the current shape of the social security system in France.\newline

The social security system has mainly been implemented after the Second World War. A general scheme was created in October, 1945 to protect workers and their family, and has been progressively extended to almost the whole population. The main objectives of the scheme were specified in the law as being to guarantee the workers and their family against the risk of reduction of their earning capacity, and to cover, for any resident unit, family, sickness or maternity and paternity-related expenditures. Autonomous schemes have been introduced in 1948 for non-farm non-wage-earners who did not want to be integrated into the general scheme. The farm scheme has developed through a social agricultural mutual insurance system protecting against traditional risks, and through mutual agricultural insurances at the margin of the system, to protect against farm-specific risks. Other special schemes have been added for certain socio-professional categories, in keeping with what existed before. From this juxtaposition of components, we see that the French social security system has reached its initial goal of generalization, but not necessarily of unity.\newline

The social security system can be divided into four branches, each one being managed by specific bodies: sickness, old-age, work accidents and family. The first one consists in a set of social insurances covering the risk of sickness, maternity, and disability, then, the other ones are a protection against work accidents, an old-age insurance and pension system, and a set of familial allowances. These branches are administered by social security funds which have a status of private law organizations with a public service assignment. The State relates to them through the Social security management. \newline

 This organization has been supplemented with complementary pension schemes to provide an additional support to the one offered by the general scheme: the two main organizations are the ARRCO (Association pour le r\'egime de retraite compl\'ementaire des salari\'es, i.e. complementary pension schemes for wage-earners) and the AGIRC (Association g\'en\'erale des institutions de retraite des cadres, i.e. complementary pension schemes for white-collar workers), which have been implemented by national inter-professional agreements, and work as a pay-as-you-go systems with contributions, voluntary at the beginning, and which became mandatory in 1970. However, they do not belong to the social security system under the supervision of the State, but are private and mandatory schemes managed by employers' and employees' representatives. Their revenues from social contributions and their spending are registered into the national accounts under public administration, but the State has no entitlement to control them.\newline

Another body has been added in 1958 to cover unemployed people, in a perspective of insurance and not of assistance, managed by the UNEDIC (Union nationale interprofessionnelle pour l'emploi dans l'industrie et le commerce, i.e. national union for industrial and commercial employment) and \textit{P\^ole Emploi} which offers to unemployed people benefits, placement and redirection services.\newline

All these schemes are financed by social contributions, which are collected by the URSSAF (Union de recouvrement des cotisations de s\'ecurit\'e sociale et d'allocations familiales, i.e. Union of collection of social security contributions and family allowances) and the ACOSS (Agence centrale des organisations de s\'ecurit\'e sociale, i.e. Central agency of social security organizations) is in charge of the treasury. The management of these spending and revenues is ruled by a budget law passed each year: \textit{la Loi de financement de la Sécurité sociale}. ACOSS differs from the proper French tax administration, the DGFIP (Direction g\'en\'erale des finances publiques, i.e. General management of public finances), which deals with the French taxes in accordance with what has been decided in the annual finance act. Then, the social security budget is different from the State budget.  \newline

We can measure the importance of the different social security schemes and the different branches mentioned above in terms of spending and revenues for 2012. The general scheme has the most important weight, and also the most important imbalance between expenditures and revenues. The funding of the base schemes of the social security rests mostly upon social security contributions, but also more and more upon tax sources.\newpage

