\section{Social security contributions}

\subsection{Main social security scheme}

Social security contributions for the general scheme are compulsory for all the recipient persons, that are the wage-earners and allied non-farm workers, and are meant to finance the four branches of the social security: sickness, old-age insurance, family allowances and work accidents and diseases. The first two branches are nominally funded both by employers and employees, while the others are financed only by employers. Social security contributions are hypothecated, each contribution being dedicated for a particular social security expenditures purpose, which explains the coexistence of different budgets for the different branches of the scheme. It is also true for other taxes financing social security schemes, such as the CSG and the CRDS: a proportion of the tax revenues funding each part of the scheme is inscribed in the law.\newline

\textbf{Social security contributions tax base}\newline

\indent The social security contribution (SSC) tax base includes all forms of labour income: earnings, bonuses, benefits in kind. We will examine the composition of the tax base in further details:
\begin{itemize}
\item the first part of the income subjected to the SSC is the earnings, variable or fixed, including the increase for special work (by night or on Sunday), and overtime hours \footnote{which are no more deductible since August, 2012}.
\item Cash benefits and bonus granted to employees for their working conditions, a personal event (marriage, birth), or their affiliation to the company (end-of-the-year bonus) are subjected to social security contributions, excepted for professional expenses or damages.
\item Tips are subjected to SSC on a fixed amount basis or on their actual value if they are registered.
\item In kind benefits are in general subjected to social security contributions and the value used for the computation is either a fixed amount or the value according to the recipient worker, that is the difference between the price of the advantage and what he pays for it. These in kind benefits include the provision of food, housing, car, computer hardware, leisure travel. \\
For the provision of food, a minimal fixed-amount is used for the computation of the SSC, excepted when the employees eat at the workplace canteen: if they contribute to its financing by more than 50\%, this in-kind benefit is not included in the contribution tax base. For hotels', cafes' and restaurants' employees, the value of the food provided is equal to a fixed-amount determined each year, in line with the minimum wage (called the \textit{minimum garanti}). It was equal to 3.49 \euro in July, 2012. Employers can choose the \textit{ticket restaurant} solution, which are luncheon vouchers used to pay lunch outside the workplace. In that case, their contribution is excluded from the tax base up to a limit of 5.29\euro per lunch and per worker in 2013. The luncheon vouchers are financed by employers in a proportion varying between 50 and 60\%, the rest being paid by employees .\\
For the provision of housing, it is considered an in-kind benefit if it is offered for free or for a small contribution not counted as a rent. Then, it is part of the tax base on the actual value or on a fixed-amount basis.\\
If the employer provides a car to his employees for free, the private use of the car is considered an in-kind benefit, and its value (according to a fixed-amount or to the actual expenditures undertaken) is included in the tax base. Regarding the home-workplace ride, it is excluded from the tax base only if it is proven that it is impossible to use public transportation, and if the employee's house is not located abnormally far from his workplace.\\
The provision of hardware and software is not part of the tax base if it does not exceed a limit of \euro2000 per worker per year. However, if it is made available permanently, the private use of this equipment is counted in the tax base.
\item Professional expenses, which include luncheon voucher or transportation allowance, are excluded on the basis of their actual value or of a fixed amount. Some occupations have a specific rate for the deduction of professional expenses, such as artists, bus drivers, or journalists for example.
\item Concerning the benefits for the breach of the work contract, those considered an income are subjected to social security contributions, and those payed as damages are exempt.
\item Employers' contributions for mandatory complementary pension schemes are excluded from the tax base, and employers' contributions for additional pension schemes, made on a voluntary basis, are excluded from the tax base under some general conditions: benefits have to be paid by one of these organizations: a contingency institution, a mutual fund, an insurance company, or a supplementary pension institution; the pension scheme has to be implemented through a collective agreement, or a ratification of the majority, or a one-sided decision from the employer, specified to all the employees; all the workers must necessarily be affiliated; and employers' contributions must not replace any other form of salary removed for less than twelve months.
\item Social security transfers for sickness, maternity, disability and death insurance, for work accident, for family allowances and for unemployment are excluded from social security contributions, whereas additional benefits paid for family protection or during a temporary inability period are subjected to social security contributions.\newline
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Computation of the social security contributions}\newline

SSC are computed by applying the legal rate to the gross wage before any deduction for other contributions (unemployment insurance, complementary pensions...). The gross earnings represent the legal basis inscribed on the work contract, generally paid monthly in France, and is used for the computation of both employers' and employees' contributions, to obtain the super-gross wage, or labour cost paid by employers, and the taxable earnings received by employees:\newline
\begin{eqnarray}
z=(1+t_r)w \\
n=(1-t_e)w
\end{eqnarray}
with z being the labour cost, w the gross earnings, $t_r$ employers' SSC rate, n the net earnings before income tax, and $t_e$ employees' SSC rate.\\
To understand the different definitions of earnings, let's take the example of a non-executive employee with \euro2000 as his gross earnings (around the middle of the distribution in France), who is single, without children, working in a company located in Paris, and with more than 20 employees:\newline

\begin{fig}[12cm]{Different definitions of earnings \label{earnings}}
{\graphique{Salairedef.pdf}} {\emph{}}
\end{fig}

The income to take into account for the calculation of the social security contributions is bounded by a an upper-limit. If there is no lower-limit - employees and employers contribute from the first euro they earn or pay - there is a minimum tax base, which is equal to the minimum wage (computed proportionally to the number of hours worked). It means that people paid below the minimum wage compute their SSC on a tax base equal to the minimum wage, excepted for people regarded as wage-earners according to the social security but not according to the labour law (students doing an internship or some managers), and for people whose contribution is computed on a fixed-amount basis. This rule applies for example to employees whose special tax base reduction for professional expenses would have reduce their tax base below the minimum wage: in that case, they pay contributions on the minimum wage. The upper-threshold can be a factor of social security ceilings, that is an amount recomputed every year and above which the income is no more subjected to the social security contributions. This amount depends on the time period chosen as a reference (an hour, a day, a month...) and corresponds to the average wage. Here are the ceilings computed for 2013:\newline

