Different contribution rates are used for each scheme (unemployment, pension, health, family, housing, etc.). They apply to the whole income, computed following the rules mentioned above, or only to a part calculated in terms of social security ceiling.\\
These rates have evolved over time: before the 1967 reform, SSC were paid to a single national social security fund, according to a rate of 6\% for the workers aged less than 65, 2\% for the workers above 65, and 15\% for the employers. Since 1967, the three branches of the Social security scheme (sickness, family and old-age) have been managed by separated bodies, and different contribution rates have been enforced. These rates have largely increased in the 1970's and the 1980's and then decreased for employers hiring low-wage workers in the 1990's, as part of a job-creation policy. An autonomy and solidarity contribution has also been created in 2004 for old-age and disabled people, and is nominally paid by employers.
\begin{itemize}
\item Sickness insurance and family allowances: the contribution rates vary according to the nature of the risk covered. Since 1980, the contribution rate for the sickness insurance branch only applies to the total income without upper-limit, and has largely increased until 1997, and then decreased down to 0.75\% for the employees in 1998, due to a transfer of the tax burden from social security contributions to the CSG. A same upward evolution is observed for employers' contributions that have reached the level of 12.8\% in 1998, without any change ever since.
    Since 1990, the contribution basis for the family allowances is no more limited by a ceiling, and the rate has decreased from 7\% in 1990 to 5.40\% in 1991, without any change ever since. Family allowances contributions are entirely paid by employers.
\item Work accidents: the contribution rate is reviewed every year and determined at the company level.
\end{itemize}

