\textbf{Alsace-Moselle special scheme}\newline

The annexation of the French territory of Alsace-Moselle to the German Empire in 1871 made if benefit from a mandatory social protection scheme from the end of the 19$^{th}$ century, with sickness, work accidents, disability and old-age insurances. When the Alsace-Moselle was reintegrated into the French territory in 1918, the German legislation for social protection was maintained, and throughout the 20$^{th}$ century the local scheme has been progressively aligned with the general scheme. However, some special rates have remained, especially for sickness insurance and work accidents: for inhabitants of Alsace-Moselle, additional contributions for sickness protection are due, to the extent of 1.6\% of the total income for the employees.\newline

\textbf{Regularisation and Payment}\newline

Social security contributions are paid every month for companies employing more than nine workers, simultaneously with the payment of the wage. A regularization has to be made every month or year to account for the variation of the income from one salary to the other, if the employee is temporarily absent from work or if he is hired in the course of the year. In that case, the social security ceiling has to be reviewed downward to account for the period the employee has been unpaid.
The payment of the contribution is made by employers to a single organization, the URSSAF (\textit{Union de recouvrement des cotisations de s\'ecurit\'e sociale et d'allocations familiales}, i.e. Union of collection of social security contributions and family allowances) of the district corresponding to the company address. The ACOSS (\textit{Agence centrale des organismes de s\'ecurit\'e sociale}, i.e. the national fund of the Urssaf) is in charge of the social security contributions treasury.


\subsection{Unemployment insurance scheme}

Unemployed people are eligible for receiving benefits from a conventional unemployment insurance scheme, financed by contributions, and from a solidarity scheme financed by the State. To set up an unemployment insurance scheme, trade and employers' unions regularly engage in bargaining to reach an agreement about the reglementation of the unemployment insurance, which is managed by the UNEDIC at the national level, in charge of the unemployment insurance, and \textit{P\^ole emploi} locally, which is the name for the job centers located throughout the country, working for the financial compensation, the training and the integration of unemployed people.\\
Unemployment insurance is mandatory for all employers working in France (mainland France, DOM and Saint-Pierre-et-Miquelon) and employing wage-earners in the private sector. \footnote{it includes those working abroad, those from France or the European Union who are expatriate, and those in a block-release training.} \newline

\textbf{Contribution tax base}\newline

The contribution tax base is the same as defined for the social security contributions, with the exceptions of the income of wage-earners above 65 and the part of the income above four social security ceilings, which are excluded from the contribution tax base.\newline

\textbf{Computation of the unemployment insurance contributions}\newline

Since 2002, the whole part of the income below four social security ceilings is subjected to the same contribution rate, whereas before this date, we distinguished between a first bracket of income corresponding to the earnings below the social security ceiling, and a second bracket corresponding to the earnings between one and four social security ceilings, with different rates applying to each bracket.\\
The rate to use for the computation of the contribution is the one applicable at the time of the payment of the earnings. Historically, the contribution rate has increased from the creation of the insurance in 1958 to 2003, and then has stabilized, as observed in the following graph:

