The important rise in 1984 was introduced at a time of crisis for the general scheme of the social security, and of continuous increase of unemployment. In 1993, another sharp  increase has been decided in a context of deep financial troubles: an economic crisis weakened economic growth and the payroll which finances the contributions has very little increased.\newline

In addition to this unemployment insurance, each employer has to pay a contribution to the AGS (Association pour la gestion du r\'egime de garantie des cr\'eances des salari\'es), to guarantee his employees the payment of what he owes to them in case of tax adjustment or compulsory liquidation.

\subsection{Complementary pension schemes}

It is mandatory for all the wage-earners belonging to the general pension scheme to become affiliated to a complementary pension scheme that provides supplement to the old-age insurance of the general scheme. The first scheme, Arrco (\textit{Association pour le r\'egime de retraite compl\'ementaire des salari\'es}, i.e. Association for the wage-earners' complementary pension scheme), created in 1961, is designed for blue-collar workers, and for the bracket A of executives' earnings (the part of the earnings below the social security ceiling). The second scheme, Agirc (\textit{Association g\'en\'erale des institutions de retraite des cadres}, i.e. General association of the institutions of executives' pensions), introduced in 1947, is financed by contributions paid on the bracket B of executives' earnings (between one and four social security ceilings), and on the bracket C of executives' earnings (between four and eight social security ceilings). More specifically, the Agirc scheme is designed for executives and allied occupations, engineers, and some managers and doctors. Each company must join a complementary pension institution member of Agirc and Arrco in a three-months delay after its creation. Here is the list of these institutions:\newline

