These institutions are called \textit{Groupes paritaires de protection sociale}, i.e. social protection groups equally managed by employees' and employers' representatives, and which are made of Agirc or Arrco funds, non-profit-making organizations such as contingency funds, and, sometimes, profit-making organizations such as insurance companies. They are 16 in total, with 29 different funds.\\
These mandatory complementary schemes can be completed by a supplementary pension scheme.\newline

Arrco and Agirc are part of a pension system working with points attributed to each employee, and converted, at the end of his career, into euros, by multiplying the number of points by the service value of a point. The employees pay contributions according to an effective rate, but the computation of their points is made according to a contractual rate that is lower: the amount of contribution they pay each year is divided by the unit buying price of a point (or reference income) to convert the contributions into points. The effective rate is calculated by multiplying the contractual rate by a calling rate (greater than 100\%), and helps to finance the scheme. Indeed, the calling rate has been adjusted upward from the 1960's to the 2000's to account for the extension of the life expectancy.\\
If we call v$_b$ the buying price of a point, v$_s$ the service value of a point, W the wage, TX the effective contribution rate (including employers' and employees' parts), and C a reduction factor which depends on the age and on the number of years the worker paid contribution to the scheme: workers can retire early, from the age of 55, but they will earn their full pension only starting from the age of 65. Before 65, the computation of the pension is made with a reduction coefficient C. Then, the computation of the pension is made as follows:

\begin{equation}
P=\frac{W\times TX}{V_b} \times V_s \times C(age, contribution)
\end{equation}


The Arrco and Agirc schemes have undergone several reforms in the 1990's to face their financing issue due to the slowing growth rate of the payroll. The 1993 and 1994 agreements consisted in a rise in the contribution rate, a suppression of the optional supplementary rates (until this date, the employers could contribute more than the compulsory rate, in a limit of 8\% for bracket 1 and 16\% for bracket 2), a reduction of the contribution return by setting the growth path of the buying price of a point higher than the growth path of the income (a point becomes proportionally more expensive to buy) and by reducing the service value of the points that were given for free according to the number of children. As shown in the preceding equation, if $V_b$ increases more than W, and if $V_s$ is reduced, the pension will be lower.\\
The 1996 agreement introduced a financial solidarity between the two schemes, as Agirc was facing more difficulty than Arrco.

\begin{description}
\item[Pensions contributions.]
The contribution tax base, since 1996, is the same as for social security contributions, with three differences: employer's contributions paid to Arrco and Agirc contributions do not enter into the contribution tax base for these schemes. In addition, complementary pension schemes contributions are always computed on the actual earnings, even when social security contributions are computed on a fixed amount basis for some specific occupations such as artists of the entertainment industry and models for occasional employers, vacation center employees, etc. Finally, a third difference is that workers can pay a contribution on a fictive income, in cases such as expatriation and some inactivity situations (mobility leave, parental leave for education, reduction of the income or the working time for example).

\item[Arrco: bracket and rate.]
Blue collar workers pay contributions to the Arrco scheme for bracket 1 (below one social security ceiling) and for bracket 2 (between one and three social security ceilings) whereas executives and allied workers pay contributions to the Arrco scheme only for bracket 1 of their wage.\newline
Since 2005, the contractual rate is equal to 6.0\% on bracket 1, and 16.0\% on bracket 2, with an effective rate of respectively 7.5\% and 20.0\% for bracket 1 and 2 (the calling rate is 125.0\% since 1992). These different rates have all increased since the 1960's, making the amount of compulsory contributions greater and greater. In particular, in 1997, the contractual rate on the second bracket has been raised up to 14\% versus 4.5\% before, for the companies whose convention has been agreed on after 1997.\\
The contribution effort is distributed among employers and employees at a rate of 60\% for the employer and 40\% for the employee, excepted if the company has been created before the 1st of January, 1999 and wants to maintain the previous distribution; if the company's convention is prior to the 25$^th$ of April, 1996; if the company agrees on a distribution more favorable to the employees.

\item[Agirc: bracket and rate.]
Executives and allied workers pay contributions to the Agirc scheme for bracket B (between one and four social security ceilings) and, since 1988, for bracket C (between four and eight social security schemes) and enjoy a guaranteed minimum of points.\\
Since 2006, the contractual rate is equal to 16.24\% for brackets B and C, and then, the effective rate is 20.3\% for brackets B and C. The distribution between employers and employees is equal to 7.70\% for the employees and 12.60\% for the employers for bracket B. Bracket C contributions effort can be distributed differently, depending on what the company agrees on, even if the last increase in the rate has necessarily been distributed as follows: +0.20 percentage points for the employees, and +0.10 percentage points for the employers.\\
Nonetheless, the companies can use a higher rate for bracket C, up to the limit of 18\%, if they were affiliated to a a senior executive pension scheme integrated to Agirc by the agreement of March, 24$^th$, 1988.\newline
A minimum amount of contribution must be paid by the employers to the Agirc instution for each executive to obtain a minimum of 120 points. This guaranteed minimum is useful for workers whose wage is under the social security ceiling, or whose part of the wage included in bracket B is not sufficient to acquire these 120 points.

\item[AGFF contribution.]
Employers must pay a contribution to the AGFF (Association for the management of the financing fund of Agirc and Arrco) for all the workers affiliated to Agirc or Arrco, even for those aged above 65. It has replaced in 2001 another contribution, the ASF, and its rate is equal to 0.80\% and 1.20\% for bracket 1, and 0.90\% and 1.30\% for bracket 2 and B, respectively for the employees and the employers.

\item[Apec scheme.]
Apec is an association for the employment of executives, engineers and technicians working on the placement of unemployed workers. It is financed by a contribution paid by the employers for each wage-earner affiliated to a pension scheme for executives, on the same tax base than for social security contributions. Its rate is equal to 0.06\% on the part of the wage under four social security ceilings, and it is divided into two parts: 0.024\% for the employee, and 0.036\% for the employer. In addition to this contribution, the executive and his employer had to pay a yearly fixed-amount of respectively \euro8.31 and \euro12.46. \footnote{It is no more the case since January, 2011}

\item[\textit{Contribution exceptionnelle temporaire} (CET)]
It is a contribution that must be paid by the workers affiliated to the Agirc scheme according to a single rate of 0.35\% (0.22\% for the employers, and 0.13\% for the employees), on a tax base corresponding to the Agirc contribution tax base, from one euro to an upper-bound of eight social security ceilings.

\end{description}




\subsection{Public sector}

Civil servants benefit from a different social security scheme, and are subjected to different contributions. There are four types of civil servants within the public sector: the State, the hospital, the local authorities or the military civil servants. They are all affiliated to the general scheme for family benefits, they pay the same rate as private sector employees, and receive the same benefits, whereas they pay a different SSC but receive the same in-kind benefits for sickness insurance.\newline

\textbf{Sickness, maternity and disability contributions}\newline

Civil servants are paid according to a base pay (called \textit{traitement}) and bonuses (called \textit{primes}) which are grade-related. The contribution tax base is made up of the base pay of civil servants which depends on their position into the hierarchy, and the bonus which is granted to some civil servants when they do a work requiring a specific skill or responsibility (called \textit{nouvelle bonification indiciaire}).\\
The contribution rate differs according to the occupation:
\begin{itemize}
\item For State's employees, it is equal to 9.70\% since 1998, and is entirely supported by the employer.
\item For hospital and local authorities public sector, the rate, entirely taken on by the employer since 1998, is equal to 11.50\%. This rate was the same since 1984, but before 1997, the employee added also his own contribution part.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Deduction for pensions}\newline

Civil servants must pay a contribution to have a right to receive a pension. The contribution tax base is the same as for sickness, maternity, and disability insurance, and a 2010 law has planned a gradual increase of the rate, entirely supported by the employees, until 2020. It is equal in 2012 to 8.39\% and should reach 10.55\% in 2020.\newline

\textbf{Employer-State's contributions for pensions}\newline

The State also pays for civil servants pensions: until 2006, it directly funded the pension scheme from the State's budget to get the accounts balanced. In 2006, a special fund, the \textit{Compte d'affectation sp\'ecial pensions} (CAS) has been created to clarify the link between the pension paid to each public sector employee, and the contributions to finance it. From now on, each public sector employer must pay SSC for his employees' pensions. The tax base is only made up of the gross base pay (bonus excluded). The civil pensions correspond to a rate of 68.59\% in 2012, and for the military pensions, the State pays according to a rate of 121.55\%, both rates having followed an upward trend for several years.\\
In addition, since 2006, the State contributes to a temporary disability allowance granted to civil servants in case of work accident or professional disease, to a rate of 0.33\%.\newline

\textbf{Additional pension scheme for public sector employees}\newline

A 2003 law, enforced in 2005, has created an additional mandatory scheme for State's, local authorities' and hospitals' employees (the \textit{r\'egime additionnel de la fonction publique}, RAFP). It works according to a point system: employees and employers both contribute with a 5\% rate and the contribution tax base is made up of the whole income (bonus included) minus the base pay and the \textit{nouvelle bonification indiciaire}, bounded by the upper-limit of 20\% of the base pay. This scheme will provide an additional transfer to the agents above the age of 60 and who receive their base pension.\newline

\textbf{Contributions to the national pension fund for local authorities agents}\newline

This scheme, the CNRACL (\textit{Caisse nationale de retraite des agents des collectivit\'es locales}), has been created on September 1947, and is the base pension scheme for civil servants in local authorities and hospitals, which provides retirement and disability pensions. The contribution tax base corresponds to the base pay and the \textit{nouvelle bonification indiciaire}, and the rate is equal to 8.39\% for employees, and 27.30\% for employers. The rate corresponding to the disability allowance part is equal to 0.50\%.\\

A special fund for hospital employment has been created in 1995 to compensate the expenditures faced by hospital employers when they grant to their employees authorizations to work part-time, professional training leave, exceptional mobility damages in case of change of the workplace, etc. It is financed by a 1\% contribution.\newline

\textbf{Contributions to the complementary pension scheme for non-permanent staff of the public service and locally elected representatives}\newline

IRCANTEC (Institution de retraite compl\'ementaire des agents non titulaires de l'Etat et des collectivit\'es publiques) is a mandatory complementary pension scheme, created in 1971, which works according to a point system.\\
 Its members are non-permanent agents of the State, territorial and hospital public service (e.g. doctors in public hospitals, %%% ajouter exemples %%%
 ), contract agents of the French central bank, of EDF-GDF (French electricity and gas industry), of public industrial and commercial firms, and also civil-servants not working full-time and not affiliated to the CNRACL, civil servants with no right to pension, mayors, deputy-mayors and other local representatives.\\
As for the Arrco and Agirc schemes, employees and employers pay an effective rate but their points are calculated on the basis of a lower theoretical rate. In 2013, on the bracket A, that is under one social security ceiling, employers pay 3.68\% (theoretical rate of 2.94\%) and employees 2.45\% (theoretical rate of 1.96\%), whereas on bracket B, that is between one and eight social security ceilings since 1992, employers pay 11.83\% (theoretical rate of 9.46\%) and employees pay 6.23\% (theoretical rate of 4.98\%).\\

The contribution tax base depends on the professional category:
\begin{itemize}
\item Wage-earners: the tax base is made up of the gross wage, any bonus related to the employment, overtime hours, in-kind benefits, work honor medal.
\item Hospital employees: the total remuneration with some bonus (or 70\% for some part-time employees).
\item Elected representatives: the same as the wage-earners.\newline
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Solidarity fund}\newline

Created in 1982, it is a national public and administrative establishment designed to collect contributions in favor of unemployed people.\\
The contribution tax base is composed of the net income, that is the gross income (the base pay + the new grade-related bonus + other additional revenues), minus the social contributions, plus the residence allowance. If the net income exceeds a certain level computed every year, the person is subjected to the contribution. In that case, we add to the contribution tax base other elements such as some bonus and overtime hours.\\
 Once the tax base is calculated, the worker must contribute at a rate of 1\%.

\section{Flat-rate income taxes}

The CSG (Contribution sociale g\'en\'eralis\'ee, i.e. Generalized social contribution) and the CRDS (Contribution au remboursement de la dette sociale, i.e. contribution to the repayment of the social debt) are flat-rate income tax collected on the gross earnings (cf. % RAPPEL GRAPH SALAIRE %
Then, these income taxes differ from the main income tax (the IRPP, \textit{imp\^ot sur le revenu des personnes physiques}) in two dimensions: the main income tax has a progressive rate, and is collected on the taxable income. The CRDS is not deductible from main income tax, whereas the CSG is partly deductible, to a rate that varies depending on the tax base.\\
Theoretically, the CSG and the CRDS are different from social security contributions as their payment does not open any entitlement to social transfers and social security affiliation, but on the other hand, they are pay-as-you-earn taxes, and are meant to finance social security. Indeed, they have been created in order to diversify the sources of financing of the social security scheme, and to reduce its deficit. Their rates have progressively increased, simultaneously with a decrease of the social security contributions rates, in a general movement of shift from social security contributions to income taxation for the financing of the social security scheme. They are collected on labour and transfers incomes and on capital, according to different conditions. The CSG has been introduced permanently whereas the CRDS was meant to be provisional. However, concerning the part on the activity and substitution incomes, the CSG and CRDS are designed to fund social security scheme, and then, are closely related to social security contributions. For the part on capital income, they have the same status as a tax and are collected by the French Treasury.\newline

\textbf{Contribution tax base}\newline

Regarding the labour income and the transfer income, the contribution tax base is almost the same that for the social security contributions, with a few differences. A deduction for professional expenses equivalent to 1.75\% is possible on some types of revenues, if they do not exceed four social security ceilings.

