\subsection{The CRDS}

In 1996 was created the CADES (Caisse d'amortissement de la dette sociale, i.e. a fund for the paying off of the the social debt), for a period of eighteen years, and was designed to work on the repayment of the social security debt. Indeed, as the contributions' revenues were not sufficient to finance all the benefits provided by the social security scheme, it has accumulated deficits that have been partly transferred to the CADES.  The fund works under the supervision of the Finance, Economy and Industry Minister. The CADES takes out loans that it repays mainly through the resources of the CRDS that has been created at the same time, and is meant to last until the extinction of the debt.\newline
Since 2001, the contribution tax base is the same that for the CSG, excepted that family, housing benefits and the minimum income are subjected to the CRDS and not to the CSG. The contribution rate is equal to 0.5\% since the creation of the CRDS, ans has never changed.

\subsection{The CSG}

Created in 1991, the CSG is part of a general reflection on the way to finance the social security scheme not only relying on the social security contributions. In the mid-1980's, the removal of the ceiling on social security contributions was completed, but other solutions were needed to raise the social security revenues: the CSG was created as a tax on the income from work and from capital, to have a larger tax base.\newline
The CSG is also deductible from the income tax, to a certain extent that depends on the type of income taxed. Since its creation, the contribution rate has largely increased, from 1.10\% in 1991 to 7.5\% in 1998 on the activity income, and the amount deductible for professional expenses has been reduced from 3\% to 1.75\% in 2011.\newline

