\section{Payroll taxes}

Some taxes paid by employers are collected on the wages of their employees, but are different from social security contributions as they are not designed to finance the social security scheme, and do not trigger any right to social transfer.

\subsection{Wage tax}

Employers must pay the wage tax in case they are not subjected to the Value added tax. The rate is equal to 4.25\%, with a supplement of 4.25\% for the part of the individual wage between \euro7,604 and \euro15,185, and another supplement of 9.35\% for the part of the individual wage above \euro15,185. In French Guiana, the rate falls to 2.55\%, and to 2.95\% in Guadeloupe, Martinique and Reunion.\\
 Since 2000, the tax base has been aligned with the social security contribution tax base. The different rates have remained unchanged since the creation of the tax, but the wage brackets are revised each year in accordance with the brackets for the income tax.

\subsection{House-building effort}

Managers employing at least twenty workers must participate in the financing of house building or related operations. The rate is at least equal to 0.45\% of the wage bill, each wage being computed in gross terms, on the same tax base as for the social security contributions. This participation often takes the form of direct investment in housing, and is calculated on the past year earnings.\\
Initially, the tax was imposed to any employer with ten or more workers, with a higher tax rate, but this has been revised in 1992.

\subsection{National fund for housing aid (FNAL: Fonds national d'aide au logement)}

The contribution to the FNAL is due by any manager employing at least one worker. It represents 0.1\% of the earnings of all the workers paying social security contributions on their actual wage or on a fixed amount basis, but not of the workers paying a fixed amount as a contribution. For managers employing twenty workers or more the rate goes up to 0.50\% for the fraction of the wage above the social security ceiling, and 0.40\% for the fraction of the wage below. The computation of the FNAL tax base is the same as for social security contributions.

\subsection{Industrial accidents' contributions}

Companies belonging to the general scheme of the social security must insure their employees for professional risks (accidents, diseases) according to a rate that is determined by the nature of the activity and the size of the company, to create a direct link between the level of risk and the amount of the contribution. For companies with less than ten employees, the rate is collective, and depends on the activity; for companies with 10 to 199 employees, the rate is a mix of a collective rate related to the activity, and the specific rate of the establishment. Above 199 employees, the rate depends entirely on the establishment and its security parameters. It is calculated by dividing the cost of work accident and professional diseases by the payroll.

\subsection{Employer's participation in in-house training}

Every employer (excepted the State, local authorities and public administrative establishments) settled or domiciled in France must participate in the financing of in-house training at a rate of 0.55\% for companies with less than ten employees, 1.05\% for companies with ten to twenty employees, and 1.60\% for companies with more than twenty employees. This last category of companies must also meet some conditions on the way this participation is realized: it should be used to finance training leave, contracts and periods of professionalisation.\\
The payment falls into two parts: one to finance contracts and periods of professionalisation and individual right to training, and one to finance training projects of the company. No matter the number of employees, employers should pay a complementary tax of 1\% in case of fixed-term contract (for this additional contribution, the tax base is the wage bill of employees on a fixed-term contract).

\subsection{Apprenticeship tax}

Introduced in 1925 to finance apprenticeship, this tax is due by all employers of a commercial, industrial or arts and craft company at a rate of 0.5\% of the payroll, with the income being computed on the same tax base than for social security contributions. This rate is raised up to 0.6\% for companies employing more than 250 workers and which do not respect the minimum quotas of trainees (4\%). Two additional contributions have been created on the same tax base: the first in 2004 for the development and the financing of the regional funds for apprenticeship, of a rate of 0.18\%, and the second in 2010 as a supplementary contribution for apprenticeship, of a rate of 0.10\%.\\
If the rate of the contribution for the development of apprenticeship has increased since its creation, the rate of the initial tax of 1925 has remained quite stable, between 0.50\% and 0.60\%.

\subsection{Transportation payment}

Designed to finance the system of public transports, it is due by employers whose company is located in the region Ile-de-France and in other French cities, and who employs a minimum number of workers, with the exception of the foundations or associations recognized as promoting the public interest, non profit-making, with social activity.\\
The subjected companies are the ones employing at least nine wage-earners according to the social security, whose workplace is located in a zone where this payment has been introduced. Itinerant workers and students doing an internship should not be taken into account. If a company owns several establishments in different zones, it is subjected to the payment only in the zones where it has more than nine employees.\newline

\textbf{Tax base and rate}\newline

The tax base is the same as for social security contributions. The wages to integrate in the computation of the payment are only those of the employees working in the zone where the tax is enforced.\\
The tax rate depends on the geographical zone that is concerned:

