\section{General reduction of employer's contributions}

\subsection{Family benefits contributions' reduction}

In a context of rising unemployment, the successive governments have designed policies to reduce the employers' contributions for family allowances in order to urge on the hiring of new people by reducing the labor cost. If the revenues of the social security will be reduced in the short-run, the idea is to make them increase in the long-run by the expansion of the laborforce and then of the payroll determining the amount of contributions to be paid. Another way to achieve the same goal is to make the financing of family benefits rest upon taxes and not only employers' contributions. It is in this perspective that the CSG has been created in 1991, whose tax base is broader than the contributions tax base. \\

Moreover, the upper-bound on the contribution tax base has been removed in 1990, the employers paying now contributions on the whole income but at a lower rate. It has decreased again in 1991 from 7.00\% to 5.40\%.

\subsubsection{From July 1993 to July 1994}

Since July 1$^{st}$, 1993, employers have been totally exempt from family benefits contributions for their employees paid below 1.1 minimum wage (called SMIC, i.e. \textit{Salaire minimum interprofessionnel de croissance}), and their contributions have been reduced by half (the rate of 5.4\% became 2.7\%) for their employees paid between 1.1 and 1.2 minimum wage.\newline

\textsc{Reference:} Law 93-353 in 07/27/1993.\\
\textsc{Source:} BSP no 22 on July 1993

