\subsection{Gradually decreasing reduction on low wages, said \og ristourne Jupp\'e \fg}

\subsubsection{Septembre 1995 - septembre 1996}

The new plan introduced a decreasing reduction of the contributions paid by the employers for social insurances, work accidents and family benefits, on wages between 1 and 1.2 minimum wage paid since September 1$^{st}$, 1995. The income ceiling was equal to 7 500 F/month on January 1996, 7 650 F/month on April 1996 and 7 688 F/month on July 1996, which corresponded to 1.2 smic. \\

This reduction could be doubled up with the exemption of family benefits contributions implemented before for employees affiliated to the general social security scheme.
The computation of the reduction is detailled here after:

$$ REDUCTION = (CEILING - Gross~wage) \times 0,64 $$

Then, the maximal reduction authorized depended on the ceiling: it was equal to 800 F on January 1996, 816F on April 1996, and 820 F on July 1996  for a full-time worker earning the minimum wage. It represented the sickness, maternity, disability and death contributions paid by the employers for an employee working 169 hours a month and earning 1 smic, that is (36,98 x 169) x 0,128 in January 1996, (37,72 x 169) x 0,128 in April 1996, and (37,91 x 169) x 0,128 in July 1996. It means that for a worker earning the minimum wage, the reduction on social security contributions added to the exemption on family contributions represented 18.2\% of his wage.  \newline

From July 1996 : for the companies affiliated to paid leave funds, the reduction increased by 10\% (the maximal reduction became 902 F)\\
For employees with incomplete hours, contract adjournment, or belonging to certain categories, specific methods were used.\\
The employer should indicate the amount of the reduction on the pay slip, and should directly calculate the reduction amount to exclude it from the payments he makes to the URSSAF.\newline

\textsc{Reference:} Law 95-882 of the 08/04/95 (JO 08/05/95). Decrees 95-942 and 943 of the 08/25/95 (JO 08/26/95)


\subsection{October 1996 - December 1997}

The 1996 Finance Act introduced a temporary merger of the two reduction and exemption packages in the period between October 1996 and December 1997,  into a single reduction for the wages paid since 10/01/1996 and between 1 and 1.33 minimum wage. The reduction was still equal to 18.2\% of the wage when the worker earned the Smic. The upper-bound wage for the reduction was equal to 8521,03 F/month, which corresponded to 1.33 Smic on October, 1996.\newline
The computation of the reduction was made as follows:\\

\begin{tabular}{ll}
  Earnings below the monthly Smic & $R = \text{Earnings} \times 0,182 $ \\
  Earnings between 1 and 1.33 Smic &  $R = (1,33.Smic - Earnings) \times 0,55$ \\
\end{tabular}\newline

The reduction increased by 10\% for companies affiliated to a paid leave fund. The maximal reduction equal to 1 166F became 1238F in that case. It corresponded to the case of full-time worker earning the minimum wage.

This reduction could not be held concurrently with other employers' contributions exemptions or the enforcement of specific rates, excepted for the abatement of part-time contributions and for the reduction granted in case of diminution or adjustment of the working time.\newline


\textsc{Reference:} 1996 Finance act 95-1236 of the 12/30/95 (JO 12/31/95). Decree 96-835 of the 09/20/96 (JO 09/22/96)\newline

However, the contributions exemptions more favorable than in the general law are maintained: it was the case for some rural areas, for new companies, and for some farming wage-earners. Then, family contributions exemption remained implemented for wages up to 1.5 smic (total exemption) and between 1.5 and 1.6 smic (partial exemption) for new companies.\\
The scheme was the following:\\
- Single decreasing reduction below 1.2 Smic (the same as the general reduction)\\
- Total exemption between 1,2 and 1,5 Smic\\
- Half-exemption (rate of 2,7\% instead of 5,4\%) between 1,5 and 1,6 Smic\newline


Source: 1998 Finance Act (JO 12/31/97)	

\subsection{January 1998 to December 1999}


\subsubsection{Single decreasing reduction}

The previous merger of the reduction of social security contributions and the family contributions exemption had been maintained, according to the same conditions as before, excepted that the wage upper-bound has been brought down to 1.3 Smic, which corresponded to 8 946,18 F/month in January 1998. The computation of the reduction was made as follows:\\

-	Earnings below the monthly minimum wage: $R= \text{Earnings} \times 0,182$\\
-	Earnings between 1 and 1.3 Smic: $R= (1,3.Smic - Earnings) \times 0,607$\\

The reduction increased by 10\% for companies affiliated to a paid leave fund. In case that the employee worked part-time, the computation was made proportionaly to the number of hours worked. The maximal reduction, for a full-time worker earning the minimum wage, was equal to 1 252,45 F.\newline

Source : 1998 Finance Act 97-1269 of the 12/30/1997 (JO 12/31/97). Decree 97-1330 of the 12/31/97 (JO 01/03/98)\newline

The family contributions exemption has been maintained for companies in some rural areas and new tax exempt companies, as specified below:\\
- Total exemption for wages below 1,5 Smic\\
- Half-exemption (rate of 2,7\% instead of 5,4\%) between 1,5 and 1,6 Smic\\

In 2000, the same system prevailed for companies which have not adopted the 35 hours-system.



\subsubsection{35 hours reduction, said \og Aubry I\fg}

Article 3 of \og loi 98-461 d'orientation et d'incitation relative \`a la r\'eduction du temps de travail \fg  of June 13$^{th}$ 1998 (called law Aubry I) introduced a fixed-amount aid which declined over time. The aid got more important when the company had agreed on a diminution of the working time, and when the diminution is large. Then, the pay scale varied according to the time of the agreement, its nature and the time passed since the agreement.\newline

\textsc{References:} Decrees' annex 98-494 of the 06/22/1998 and 2000-84 of the 01/31/2000
Lefebvre Social 2003, no 9590.

\subsection{January 2000 to July 2003}

A new exemption system had been implemented by the law 2000-37 of January 19$^{th}$ 2000. Companies which had agreed on a working time of at most 35 hours a week or 1600 hours a year and committed to create or preserve employment could benefit from social security contributions reduction.

\subsubsection{Companies which have kept the 39 hours}

Companies which had kept the 39 hours working week were still benefitting from the previous reduction decided by Jupp\'e.

\subsubsection{35 hours reduction, said \og Aubry II\fg}

The amount of the reduction should be calculated using the following formula, according to the pay scale of January 29$^{th}$:

\begin{equation}
  REDUCTION = \frac{1}{12} \times \Big[\frac{41,500~FRF \times 6881,68~FRF}{MGE} - 20,000~FRF\Big]
\end{equation}

with MGE meaning monthly gross earnings, and 6881.68 FRF being the level of the minimum wage in 2000.\\
 The minimal reduction was a fixed-amount equal to 4000 FRF per year for workers earning 1.73 Smic, and the maximal one was for workers earning the minimum wage, with a reduction equal to 26\% of their wage (21 500  FRF).\newline


\textsc{Reference:} Decree 2000-73 of January 28$^{th}$ 2000 - art. 1 JORF January 29$^{th}$ 2000; Article D241-13 of the social security Code.


In 2003, the formula has been revised:
\begin{equation}
  REDUCTION = \frac{1}{12} \times \Big[\frac{\euro6,720~ \times \text{Monthly~SMIC}}{MGE} - \euro3238,57~ \Big]
\end{equation}

\textsc{Sources:} Lefebvre Social 2000, p. 95; Lefebvre Social 2003, p. 84

\subsection{Fillon exemptions}

In the 2003-2005 period, the minimum wage had been harmonized, and, as a consequence, to treat all the companies fairly, and to make them pay exactly the same minimum wage, the minimal cost of labor should also be harmonized between the companies, whatever the working time system they chose (35 or 39 hours). It was in this perspective that a new plan for employer's contributions reduction on low wages had been designed.

\subsubsection{Measures on July 1$^{st}$, 2003}

The new system of contributions exemption replaced the former measures of the single decreasing reduction and the law Aubry II. It was a system of decreasing reduction of employers' social security contributions, for wages below 1.7 Smic. It was enforced for employers paying for a mandatory unemployment insurance scheme, for employers of workers in public companies, public industrial and commercial firms, local authorities, and employers affiliated to specific schemes of mines, sailors, clerk and notary employee.\\
The reduction was equal to the monthly gross income multiplied by a coefficient. Until June, 30$^{th}$, the companies used a different coefficient depending on whether or not they previously benefitted from the reduction of the contributions granted by the law Aubry II. If they benefitted from it, the formula was as follows:\\

\begin{equation}
  REDUCTION = MGE \times \Big[\frac{0,26}{0,7}\Big]\times \Big[1,7 \times \frac{Hourly~SMIC \times NBHP}{MGE} - 1\Big]
\end{equation}

with NBHP being the number of hours paid (the one mentioned in the pay slip). The reduction had an upper-bound equal to 0.26 MGI.\newline

If the company did not benefitted from the Aubry II contributions reduction, the formula to use was this one:\\

\begin{equation}
  REDUCTION = MGE \times \Big[\frac{0,208}{0,5}\Big]\times \Big[1,5 \times \frac{Hourly~SMIC \times NBHP}{MGE} - 1\Big]
\end{equation}
 for wages paid between July 1$^{st}$ 2003 and June 30$^{th}$ 2004, and:\\

\begin{equation}
  REDUCTION = MGE \times \Big[\frac{0,234}{0,6}\Big]\times \Big[1,6 \times \frac{Hourly~SMIC \times NBHP}{MGE} - 1\Big]
\end{equation}

 for wages paid between July 1$^{st}$ 2004 and June 30$^{th}$ 2005.\newline


\textsc{Sources:} Decree 2003-487 of June 11$^{th}$ 2003 enforcing title III of the law 2003-47 of January 17$^{th}$ 2003
related to wages, working time, employment development and modifying social security code (modified by the decree 2005-88 of February 4$^{th}$ 2005).\\

Decree 2004-821 of august 18$^{th}$ 2004 enforcing  some special social security schemes of title III of the January 17$^{th}$ 2003 law 2003-47
related to wages, working time, employment development and modifying the social security code (modified by the decree 2005-948 of August 2$^{nd}$ 2005).\\

\subsubsection{Measures on July 1$^{st}$, 2005}

Starting from July 2005, all the companies applied the same following formula:

\begin{equation}
  REDUCTION = MGE \times \Big[\frac{0,26}{0,6}\Big]\times \Big[1,6 \times \frac{Hourly~SMIC \times NBHP}{MGE} - 1\Big]
\end{equation}

\subsubsection{Measures on July 1$^{st}$, 2007}

The measure had been slightly revised to apply to wages below 1.6 Smic, following the same conditions as before. The formula to compute the reduction amount had also been modified, depending on the company's number of employees.\newline

\textbf{Companies with more than 20 employees:}
\begin{equation}
  REDUCTION = MGE \times \Big[\frac{0,26}{0,6}\Big]\times \Big[1,6 \times \frac{Hourly~SMIC \times NBHP}{MGE} - 1\Big]
\end{equation}

\textbf{Companies with 1 to 19 employees:}
\begin{equation}
  REDUCTION = MGE \times \Big[\frac{0,281}{0,6}\Big]\times \Big[1,6 \times \frac{Hourly~SMIC \times NBHP}{MGE} - 1\Big]
\end{equation}

References: article 41-V of the 2007 finance act 2006-1666 of December 21$^{st}$ 2006 and article 53-VII of the law 2007-290
of March 5$^{th}$ 2007 establishing the enforceable right to housing and related to different measures promoting social cohesion.

\subsubsection{Measure on October 1$^{st}$, 2007}

The reference to the hourly minimum wage into the formula was replaced by the use of the monthly minimum wage (overtime hours excluded). The formula became:\newline

\textbf{Companies with more than 20 employees:}
\begin{equation}
  REDUCTION = MGE \times \Big[\frac{0,26}{0,6}\Big]\times \Big[1,6 \times \frac{Monthly~SMIC}{MGE} - 1\Big]
\end{equation}

\textbf{Companies with 1 to 19 employees:}
\begin{equation}
  REDUCTION = MGE \times \Big[\frac{0,281}{0,6}\Big]\times \Big[1,6 \times \frac{Monthly~SMIC}{MGE} - 1\Big]
\end{equation}


References: law 2007-1223 of August 21$^{st}$ 2007 in favor of work, employment and purchasing power.

\subsubsection{Measures on January 1$^{st}$ 2011}

The 2011 modification of the Fillon exemption had replaced the reference to the monthly minimum wage by a yearly minimum wage, in order to avoid some optimization that made employers pay different contributions amounts for a same annual earnings but with a different distribution over the year.\newline

\textbf{Companies with more than 20 employees:}
\begin{equation}
  REDUCTION = MGE \times \Big[\frac{0,26}{0,6}\Big]\times \Big[1,6 \times \frac{Yearly~SMIC}{YGE} - 1\Big]
\end{equation}

with YGE the yearly gross earnings\newline

\textbf{Companies with 1 to 19 employees:}
\begin{equation}
  REDUCTION = MGE \times \Big[\frac{0,281}{0,6}\Big]\times \Big[1,6 \times \frac{Yearly~SMIC}{YGE} - 1\Big]
\end{equation}

with YGE the yearly gross earnings\newline

Reference: 2011 Bill for the financing of the social security



